Insurance Claim Prediction Model

Lead Data Analyst: Sunday Osagie

Objective: Build a predictive model to determine the probability of a building having at least one insurance claim over the insured period based on building characteristics.
Target: 'Claim' (1 = at least one claim, 0 = no claim).

Data Cleaning and Preprocessing

In[7]:
# Drop non-predictive IDs
df.drop(['Customer Id', 'Geo_Code'], axis=1, inplace=True, errors='ignore')

# Clean NumberOfWindows
if 'NumberOfWindows' in df.columns:
    df['NumberOfWindows'] = (
        df['NumberOfWindows']
        .astype(str)
        .str.strip()
        .replace({' .': np.nan, '>=10': '10'})
    )
    df['NumberOfWindows'] = pd.to_numeric(df['NumberOfWindows'], errors='coerce')

# Handle Date_of_Occupancy and create Building Age
if 'Date_of_Occupancy' in df.columns:
    # Convert to year
    df['Date_of_Occupancy'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Date_of_Occupancy'], errors='coerce').dt.year

    # Impute missing values
    from sklearn.impute import SimpleImputer
    imputer = SimpleImputer(strategy='median')
    df['Date_of_Occupancy'] = imputer.fit_transform(df[['Date_of_Occupancy']]).astype(int)

    # Calculate Building_Age
    df['Building_Age'] = df['YearOfObservation'] - df['Date_of_Occupancy']
    df['Building_Age'] = df['Building_Age'].clip(lower=0, upper=150)

    # Drop the original column
    df.drop('Date_of_Occupancy', axis=1, inplace=True)

# Rename & clean Building Dimension
if 'Building Dimension' in df.columns:
    df.rename(columns={'Building Dimension': 'Building_Dimension'}, inplace=True)
    df['Building_Dimension'] = imputer.fit_transform(df[['Building_Dimension']])
    
    # Handle outliers using IQR
    q1 = df['Building_Dimension'].quantile(0.25)
    q3 = df['Building_Dimension'].quantile(0.75)
    iqr = q3 - q1
    df['Building_Dimension'] = df['Building_Dimension'].clip(
        lower=q1 - 1.5*iqr,
        upper=q3 + 1.5*iqr
    )

# Final missing values check
print("\nMissing Values After Cleaning:")
print(df.isna().sum())

# Check numeric and categorical columns
numeric_cols = df.select_dtypes(include=['int64', 'float64']).columns.tolist()
categorical_cols = df.select_dtypes(include=['object']).columns.tolist()

print("\nNumeric Columns:", numeric_cols)
print("Categorical Columns:", categorical_cols)

Data Preprocessing Pipeline and Hyperparameter Tuning

In[16]:
numeric_transformer = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='median')),
    ('scaler', StandardScaler())
])

categorical_transformer = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='most_frequent')),
    ('encoder', OrdinalEncoder(handle_unknown='use_encoded_value', unknown_value=-1))
])

preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers=[
        ('num', numeric_transformer, num_cols),
        ('cat', categorical_transformer, cat_cols)
    ]
)

TrainTest Split Strategy

To evaluate how well the model generalizes to unseen data, the dataset is split into training and testing sets.

  • Training set: Used to train the machine learning models.
  • Testing set: Used strictly for evaluating model performance.

A stratified split is applied to preserve the original distribution of the target variable (Claim) in both sets, which is critical due to class imbalance.

This approach ensures fair evaluation and reduces the risk of biased performance metrics.

In[17]:
# Train-Test Split
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

X = df.drop('Claim', axis=1)
y = df['Claim']
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X, y, test_size=0.2, stratify=y, random_state=42
)

Modeling & Evaluation

In[19]:
def train_evaluate(model, name, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, preprocessor):
    pipeline = ImbPipeline(steps=[
        ('preprocessor', preprocessor),
        ('smote', SMOTE(random_state=42)),
        ('classifier', model)
    ])
    
    param_grid = {}
    if name == 'Logistic Regression':
        param_grid = {
            'classifier__C':[0.1,1,10],
            'classifier__solver':['liblinear'],
            'classifier__max_iter':[500]
        }
    elif name == 'Random Forest':
        param_grid = {
            'classifier__n_estimators':[50,100],
            'classifier__max_depth':[10,20]
        }
    elif name == 'XGBoost':
        param_grid = {
            'classifier__n_estimators':[100,200],
            'classifier__max_depth':[3,5,7],
            'classifier__learning_rate':[0.01,0.1]
        }
    
    cv = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=42)
    grid = GridSearchCV(
        estimator=pipeline, param_grid=param_grid, cv=cv, scoring='f1', n_jobs=-1, verbose=1
    )
    grid.fit(X_train, y_train)
    
    y_pred = grid.predict(X_test)
    y_prob = grid.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1] if hasattr(grid.best_estimator_, 'predict_proba') else None
    
    print(f"\nBest Params for {name}: {grid.best_params_}")
    print(f"\nClassification Report for {name}:\n{classification_report(y_test, y_pred)}")
    
    if y_prob is not None:
        roc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_prob)
        print(f'ROC-AUC for {name}: {roc:.4f}')
        
        # Precision-Recall Curve
        precision, recall, _ = precision_recall_curve(y_test, y_prob)
        plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
        plt.plot(recall, precision, marker='.')
        plt.title(f'Precision-Recall Curve for {name}')
        plt.xlabel('Recall')
        plt.ylabel('Precision')
        plt.show()
    else:
        roc = None
    
    # Confusion Matrix
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
    plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues')
    plt.title(f'Confusion Matrix for {name}')
    plt.ylabel('Actual')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.show()
    
    return grid.best_estimator_, roc, y_pred

Train & Evaluate Models

In[21]:
models = {
    'Logistic Regression': LogisticRegression(random_state=42),
    'Random Forest': RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42),
    'XGBoost': XGBClassifier(random_state=42, eval_metric='logloss')
}

best_models = {}
roc_scores = {}
y_preds = {}

for name, model in models.items():
    print(f"\n====== {name} =======")
    best_models[name], roc_scores[name], y_preds[name] = train_evaluate(
        model, name, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, preprocessor
    )

Model Comparison Table

In[23]:
comparison = []

for name in models.keys():
    f1 = classification_report(
        y_test,
        y_preds[name],
        output_dict=True
    )['1']['f1-score']

    acc = (y_preds[name] == y_test).mean()

    comparison.append({
        'Model': name,
        'F1-Score': round(f1, 4),
        'Accuracy': round(acc, 4),
        'ROC-AUC': round(roc_scores[name], 4) if roc_scores[name] else None
    })

comparison_df = pd.DataFrame(comparison).sort_values(
    by='F1-Score',
    ascending=False
)

print("\nModel Comparison:")
print(comparison_df)

Feature Importance Interpretation

The most influential features provide valuable business insights:

  • Building Age: Older buildings are more likely to experience structural failures, increasing claim probability.
  • Building Dimensions: Larger structures typically carry higher exposure and risk.
  • Insured Period Length: Longer coverage periods increase the likelihood of at least one claim occurrence.
  • Usage Type: Commercial buildings often show higher claim frequency than residential ones.

These insights can support:

  • Risk-based premium pricing
  • Preventive maintenance strategies
  • Improved underwriting decisions

FINAL MODEL SELECTION & JUSTIFICATION

Selected Model: XGBoost

  • Best Predictive Performance: (It achieved the highest F1-Score, making it most effective for handling class imbalance and reducing missed claim cases).
  • Strong Class Separation: (It recorded the highest ROC-AUC, indicating superior ability to distinguish between claim and non-claim policies).
  • Meaningful Feature Importance: (It effectively identifies key risk-driving variables and captures complex, non-linear relationships in the data).
  • Business Relevance: (It improves claim risk assessment, supports better pricing decisions, and enhances loss control strategies).

Final Statement: XGBoost is selected for deployment because it provides the most reliable balance between model accuracy, interpretability, and business impact for insurance claim prediction.

Business Interpretation & Key Insights

1. Business Interpretation

  • Predicts if a building will have 1 insurance claim during the policy period.
  • Observed claim rate: 22.8% (~1 in 45 buildings)
  • Value: Enables proactive, risk-based underwriting, pricing, and loss prevention.

2. Key Insights

Feature Insight
Building Size Larger buildings (~3,126 m vs 1,515 m) higher claim risk
Settlement (Rural/Urban) Rural: ~25% vs Urban: ~20.6% higher natural peril & response risk
Maintenance Not painted/fenced or no garden elevated risk
Building Type Type 4 > Type 3 > Type 2 > Type 1 increasing risk
Number of Windows More windows higher exposure
Building Age Minimal standalone impact (~4647 years)

3. Recommendations

  • Risk-Based Pricing: Tiered rates based on predicted probability (10%, 1025%, 2540%, >40%)
  • Auto-referrals: Large buildings, rural + unpainted, Type 34
  • Loss Prevention: Painting, fencing, garden maintenance, window protection; discounts for verified improvements
  • Portfolio Strategy: Target high-risk tail for reinsurance; monitor high-risk zones
  • Operations: Integrate model into quoting/underwriting; train teams on key risk signals
  • Governance: Retrain annually; monitor calibration; enrich features (roof, occupancy, location, claims history)

Expected Impact: 515% improvement in loss ratio over 23 years through better risk selection, pricing, and focused loss prevention.

Limitations and Future Improvements

Limitations

  • The dataset is imbalanced, which may bias predictions toward the majority class.
  • Temporal factors such as claim timing were not explicitly modeled.
  • External environmental factors (weather, location risk) are not included.

Future Improvements

  • Incorporate external datasets such as weather or geospatial risk data.
  • Apply SHAP or LIME for enhanced model explainability.
  • Explore time-based modeling to capture claim occurrence patterns.
  • Deploy the model as a web API or dashboard for real-time risk assessment.
